Introduction¶

This dataset is on Loan and their outcomes. The loan disbursing organization is Prosper. This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. For this analysis, I will focus on the variables below. I believe I will be able to demonstrate my skills and come up with useful observations on the loan data.

The variables are:

  • Term: The length of the loan expressed in months.
  • Loan Status: The current status of the loan: Cancelled, Chargedoff, Completed, Current, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue. The PastDue status will be accompanied by a delinquency bucket.
  • BorrowerAPR: The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.
  • ProsperScore: A custom risk score built using historical Prosper data. The score ranges from 1-10, with 10 being the best, or lowest risk score. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.
  • ListingCategory: The category of the listing that the borrower selected when posting their listing: 0 - Not Available, 1 - Debt Consolidation, 2 - Home Improvement, 3 - Business, 4 - Personal Loan, 5 - Student Use, 6 - Auto, 7- Other, 8 - Baby & Adoption, 9 - Boat, 10 - Cosmetic Procedure, 11 - Engagement Ring, 12 - Green Loans, 13 - Household Expenses, 14 - Large Purchases, 15 - Medical/Dental, 16 - Motorcycle, 17 - RV, 18 - Taxes, 19 - Vacation, 20 - Wedding Loans
  • BorrowerState: The two letter abbreviation of the state of the address of the borrower at the time the Listing was created.
  • Occupation: The Occupation selected by the Borrower at the time they created the listing.
  • EmploymentStatusDuration: The length in months of the employment status at the time the listing was created.
  • EmploymentStatus: The employment status of the borrower at the time they posted the listing.
  • AvailableBankCardCredit: The total available credit via bank card at the time the credit profile was pulled.
  • StatedMonthlyIncome: The monthly income the borrower stated at the time the listing was created.
  • LoanNumber: Unique numeric value associated with the loan.
  • LoanOriginationQuarter: The quarter in which the loan was originated.
  • Recommendations: Number of recommendations the borrower had at the time the listing was created.

I will be exploring based on the folowing broad research question:

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

My variable of interest is LoanStatus. It is a categorical variable. Majority of the loans are current and a few are charged off. Some have been completed while others are past due for over 60 days.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

As shown in the series of analysis, most of the numeric variables (e.g StatedMonthlyIncome, AvailableBankcardCredit, EmploymentStatusDuration etc) are skewed to the right. This is because there are outliers in such variables. I performed some transformations. I perform log transformations to better understand the distribution of the variables. For some variables, I tinkered with the bin sizes for better visualization. In the case of Recommendations, I also partitioned the variable into normal and outliers for better visualization. I used pie chart to view the outliers.

This relationship is negative. Th higher the stated monthly income, the lower the category of loans applied for. It should be noted that these lower categories are concerned mainly with long term investments such as Home Improvement, Boat and others. As can be seen from the correlations heat map, the correlations between the variables are very weak. Next, I will visualize the discrete variables.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

As documented above, Loan status varies in different ways.

  • Borrrowers in full time employment have higher rate of loan completion.
  • The higher the number of recommendations, the higher the loan completion rate.
  • Long term loans have better loan outcome status than short term loans.
  • The higher the employment status, stated monthly income, and available bank card credit of borrowers, the lower the rate of defaults and charged offs.
  • Also, these lower category loans have high rate of loan completion.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Yes. I observed that borrowers with high stated income often go for lower category loans. These loans are usually long term. Such loans include Boat loans, Business Loans, Home Improvement etc. Moreover, I observed that the relationship between monthly income and employment duration, although positive, is very weak.

Multivariate Exploration¶

In this section, I will investigate this dataset further by creating multivariate plots. Since I have begin to see pattern on how some variables affect Loan Status, I will pull these variables together in a plot and try to understand them much deeper.

Let us begin.

In [23]:
# Visualizing the relationship of term to Available Bank Card Credit and Stated Monthly Income

g.add_legend();

From the above charts, it appears that there is a somewhat linear relationship between stated monthly income, available card credit and loan term. As borrowers' monthly income increases, their card credit increases and they tend to go for 36 month term loans.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

It became clearer that income, bank balance, listing category has a great influence on loan outcome status. Borrowers with higher monthly income has higher card credit, obtains lower category listing loans and have better loan completion status. Generally, higher monthly income tends to encourage favourable loan completion status.

Moreover Employment Status Duration, Available Bank card Credit and Recommendation have some relationship. It appears that the higher the employment duration, the higher the stated monthly income and the higher the number of recommendations. The higher the Available Bank card credit, the higher the number of recommendations.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

It is surprising to observe that Employment Status Duration and Available Bank card Credit do not have a linear relationship. Even when transformed, the relationship is very weak. I had expected the two to be strongly correlated.

Observations¶

From the various plots, I have observed that Loan Status often term loan outcome status is influenced by a lot of variables in different ways. For favourable loan outcome, such variables as income, bank credit, recommendations, employment status and employment status duration plays a great part. The better these variables are, the better the loan outcome status.

Conclusions¶

Conclusively, although it is clear that the variables analyzed here affects loan status, it is necessary to dig deeper either by adding other variables or by carrying out a regression analysis.
